4. How QA Should Test This (Test Scenarios)

This is the most important part for the tester team.

Test Scenario 1: Simulated Equifax Timeout

Setup
	•	Configure the Equifax DIT endpoint (in lower env or via test hook) to:
	•	Delay response beyond client timeout, OR
	•	Throw a simulated runtime exception

Steps
	1.	Initiate phone verification for a test user
	2.	Trigger the Equifax DIT call
	3.	Observe the application behavior

Expected Result
	•	Phone verification completes with a FAIL (or REVIEW) decision
	•	No unhandled exception in logs
	•	No repeated ERROR logs for the same user
	•	Workflow does not retry indefinitely

⸻

Test Scenario 2: Null / Empty Equifax Response

Setup
	•	Simulate Equifax returning:
	•	Empty response body
	•	Unparseable JSON
	•	Explicit null response

Steps
	1.	Initiate phone verification
	2.	Allow Equifax call to return null/empty

Expected Result
	•	System treats response as error
	•	No NullPointerException
	•	Phone verification returns FAIL
	•	Workflow continues normally

⸻

Test Scenario 3: HTTP 500 from Equifax

Setup
	•	Simulate Equifax returning HTTP 500

Steps
	1.	Initiate phone verification
	2.	Observe retry and result

Expected Result
	•	System handles error gracefully
	•	No infinite retries
	•	Controlled FAIL response returned
	•	Single ERROR log entry per attempt

⸻

Test Scenario 4: Regression – Successful Equifax Response

Setup
	•	Normal Equifax DIT success response

Steps
	1.	Initiate phone verification
	2.	Complete workflow normally

Expected Result
	•	Phone verification decision PASS/REVIEW based on Equifax response
	•	Trust values populated correctly
	•	No change to existing successful behavior

